data.content:
Your code **doesn't use `Thread.Abort`**, so there's nothing broken to fix — but the raw `Thread` pattern is outdated for .NET 8. Here's the key guidance:

## `Thread.Abort` in .NET 5+

`Thread.Abort()` throws **`PlatformNotSupportedException`** at runtime. The modern replacement is **`CancellationToken`** for cooperative cancellation.

## Recommended migration

Replace raw threads with `Task` + `CancellationToken`:

```csharp
public class SimpleWorker
{
    public async Task RunBatchAsync(List<WorkItem> items,
        CancellationToken ct = default)
    {
        var tasks = items.Select(item =>
            Task.Run(() => Process(item, ct), ct));

        await Task.WhenAll(tasks);
    }

    private void Process(WorkItem item, CancellationToken ct)
    {
        ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
        Thread.Sleep(100); // consider await Task.Delay(100, ct);
        item.Result = ComputeResult(item.Input);
    }
}
```

## Quick reference

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 replacement |
|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` |
| `ThreadAbortException` | `OperationCanceledException` |
| `Thread` + `Start/Join` | `Task.Run` + `await Task.WhenAll` |
| `Thread.Sleep` | `await Task.Delay(ms, ct)` |

The caller controls cancellation via `CancellationTokenSource`:

```csharp
using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout: TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
await worker.RunBatchAsync(items, cts.Token);
// call cts.Cancel() to stop early
```
